-- Kernel-run bounds proof: an FTI write past capacity is UNSAT at solve
-- time, so the kernel halts with exit 2 (the project's UNSAT halt code).
--
--     evident-oracle emit tests/fti_proofs/overrun_unsat.ev main -o /tmp/overrun.smt2
--     kernel /tmp/overrun.smt2   # expect exit 2
--
-- This is the live form of PROOF 1: instead of a static sat-check, the
-- bound `write_slot < capacity` is asserted into the per-tick Z3 query
-- the kernel runs. The FSM deliberately drives write_slot = capacity, so
-- the very first solve is UNSAT and Z3 refuses the tick. With
-- EVIDENT_UNSAT_CORE=1 the kernel names this constraint as the culprit —
-- exactly the diagnostic the driver's `lx_count < 65534` bound gives.
--
-- expect: exit = 2
import "stdlib/kernel.ev"

claim main
    capacity ∈ Int = 4
    -- The buffer is full; the next write targets slot = capacity.
    write_slot ∈ Int = 4
    -- The load-bearing safety constraint. write_slot = 4 ≮ capacity = 4
    -- ⇒ no satisfying assignment ⇒ UNSAT ⇒ kernel exit 2.
    write_slot < capacity
    effects ∈ Seq(Effect) = ⟨Exit(0)⟩
